## Output structure (MANDATORY)

```markdown
# Plan — <title>

## 1. Task DAG (mermaid)

\`\`\`mermaid
graph TD
    T1[task 1: ...] --> T3[task 3: ...]
    T2[task 2: ...] --> T3
    T3 --> T4
\`\`\`

Every node ID (T1, T2, ...) is referenced in §2 with concrete description.

## 2. Task descriptions

For each Tn:
- Owner (agent profile: planner | architect | coder | reviewer | tester)
- Inputs (artifact refs from upstream)
- Output (artifact ref this task produces)
- Acceptance criteria (1 sentence each, verifiable)

## 2.5 Cross-stage memory awareness (MANDATORY — Phase 2.D #13)

List every open memory hit whose `[stage]` appears in any of the downstream
task owners (architect, contract, coder, verify, review, integrate). Format:

| stage | failurePattern (≤ 80 chars) | does this run's plan address the fix? | risk-ref if not |
|-------|----------------------------|---------------------------------------|-----------------|

- "address" means: at least one task in §2 explicitly applies the fix's
  instruction (e.g. the fix says "Read implement.md before grep" → plan §2
  must show verify task taking `read_from_disk: true`)
- If "no" → MUST raise a risk in §3 below with `Escalate if...` referencing
  this memory entry's failurePattern verbatim
- Empty table = either no cross-stage memory exists (rare; check memory hits
  section above) OR you intentionally claim every entry is irrelevant for
  this run — state that explicitly in 1 line after the table

## 3. Risk register (LCO-style)

| ID | Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation | Escalate if... |
|----|------|-----------|--------|------------|----------------|

Each risk gets an ID (R1, R2, ...) referenced by downstream stages.

## 4. Decisions deferred to architecture

Things you intentionally did NOT decide in plan because architecture should
have the full context. Be explicit so architecture can't claim you punted
silently.

- D1: <decision> — defer to architecture because <reason>

## 5. LCO anchor commitment

Mark the explicit go/no-go statement:
- ✅ **GO**: the task DAG is sufficient to deliver the success criteria from
  intake, given the risks above.
- ❌ **NO-GO**: <reason> — escalate to user before architecture stage.

If you can't honestly commit to GO, output NO-GO with a specific reason.
Architecture will not run if plan ends NO-GO.

## 6. Design-stage handoff (one paragraph)

What architecture must investigate first; which intake unknowns are
blocking; which research counter-evidence to revisit.

## 7. Implement fan-out declaration (OPTIONAL — v0.3 / v1 fan-out)

If the implement stage is naturally splittable into 2-4 independent
parallel sub-implements (e.g. backend + frontend + tests; or
domain-module-1 + domain-module-2 + domain-module-3), emit a
`parallel:` block. Otherwise omit this section entirely.

```yaml
parallel:
  - id: T-impl-a
    name: backend                          # /^[A-Za-z0-9_.:-]+$/ (shell-safe per RISK-Q4-c)
    affects: ^packages/backend/             # path regex; MUST NOT overlap with other entries
  - id: T-impl-b
    name: frontend
    affects: ^packages/frontend/
  - id: T-impl-c
    name: tests
    affects: ^(packages/.*/__tests__|tests)/
```

Hard rules for the `parallel` block:
- ≥ 2 entries (a 1-entry parallel isn't a fan-out — use single
  implement instead)
- ≤ 4 entries (plan-roadmap concurrency cap; SmartBear 400-LOC
  research per Pilot-02 motivates keeping per-patch attention bounded)
- `name` MUST match `/^[A-Za-z0-9_.:-]+$/` (shell-safe + becomes
  filename `implement-<name>.md`)
- `affects` regex MUST NOT overlap with any other entry's `affects`
  (verify stage validator will reject overlaps as plan bug)
- No nested fan-out in v1 (child sub-implements cannot themselves
  declare `parallel:`)
```

## Hard limits

- ≤ 1500 words (counted)
- DAG must have ≥ 2 nodes (or it's not a DAG — flag as "too small for AISEP,
  do directly")
- Every risk MUST have a likelihood + impact + mitigation; no "TBD" allowed
- Commitment line (GO / NO-GO) is mandatory
- §2.5 Cross-stage memory awareness table is REQUIRED whenever the Memory
  hits section above is non-empty. Missing the table when memory hits exist
  is a NO-GO (per Phase 2.D #13: unfixed memory entries must not become
  folklore by being silently ignored at plan time)
